         <div type="commentary">
            <!-- NOTES emfr
Le nom du roi est en sanskrit sur le sceau et en prâkrit dans le texte des plaques. EI 8, p. 145 : rapprochement avec les formules des tablettes de Guṇapadēya. 
Dani (1963) : inscr. de Mayidavolu dans le même style qu’une inscription des Br̥hatphalāyana (toutes dérivant des inscriptions des Ikṣvāku).
Pollock (1996, p. 211, n. 18).
Pollock (2006, p. 63, note 49). ― Les situe erronément  au TN et les présente comme p-ê les tablettes les plus anciennes d’Asie du Sud. ― « With the Sanskrit of the Pallava seals compare the contemporaneous charter of Jayavarman, Kistna district, Tamilnadu (EI 6: 315–19; possibly the oldest copperplate record in South Asia). The charter is in Prakrit, whereas the seal reads: br̥hatphalāyanasagotrasya mahārājaśrījayavarmmaṇaḥ; contrast this with lines 4–5 of the plate itself: br̥hatphalāyanasagoto rājā sirijayavammo. The Sanskrit is also written in different characters from the Prakrit. » Compare Salomon (1998, p. 114) : « The earliest specimens of copper plate charters come from southern India, issued by the early Pallava and Śālaṅkāyana dynasties and datable, according to Sircar (SIE 107), to about the middle of the fourth century A.D. »
Sivaramamurti (1948, p. 168) : tablettes Br̥hatphalāyana de Jayavarman à Koṇḍamudi (EI 6, p. 315) reprennent l’écriture des tablettes de Mayidavōlu.
Willis’ project map : Br̥hatphalāyana: Kondamudi copper plates of Jayavarman ― This set of 8 copper plates were discovered in the village of Kondamudi and were secured together with a ring and seal. The seal is stamped with an image of a trident, a box, a crescent moon and a circular legend which is written in different characters to those found on the copper plates. ― The charter records that Mahārāja Jayavarman donated the village of Pāṇṭūra in the district of Kūdūra to 8 Brāhmaṇas. The donated village was split into 24 shares and divided between the Brāhmaṇas as follows: 
Śarvaguptārya, a householder of the Gautama gotra – 8 shares
Savigija of the Tānavya gōtra – 3 shares
Goginaja – 3 shares
Bhavannaja of the Kauṇinya gōtra – 2 shares
Rudavennhuja of the Bhāradvāja gōtra – 1 ½ shares
Tśvaradattārya of the Kārshṇāyana gōtra – 1 ½ shares
Rudaghōshārya of the Aupamanyava gōtra – 1 share
Skandarudrārya of the Kauśika gōtra – ½ share 
(This division does not total 24 shares however).
The charter was issued from Kūdūra on the 1st day of the 1st fortnight of winter in the 10th year of Jayavarman’s reign. The donated village was made as brahmadēya and Jayavarman is described in the inscription as belonging to the Br̥hatphalāyana gōtra and a worshipper of Mahēśvara, a form of Śiva. The donation was made to increase the donor’s life span and to secure victory in war. (Hultzsch, E., ‘Kondamudi plates of Jayavarman’, Epigraphia Indica vol VI, pp. 315-319.) ― Sircar, Altekar and Majumdar date Jayavarma’s reign to around the end of the 3rd century and the beginning of the 4th century AD, suggesting he was a contemporary of the early Gupta kings. (Altekar, A.S. & Majumdar, R.C. The Vākāṭaka-Gupta Age, Motilal Banarsi Dass, 1954, p.63 and Sircar. D.C., The Successors of the Sātavāhanas, University of Calcutta, 1939, p. 41)
Br̥hatphalāyana: Guduru/Kudūra? ― According to Sircar, the modern village of Guduru is located on the ancient city of Kudūra, the place of issue of the Kondamudi copper-plates of Jayavarma. (Sircar. D.C., The Successors of the Sātavāhanas, University of Calcutta, 1939, p. 46) ― Jayavarman's plates date in 10th regnal year and identify him as belonging to the Br̥hatphalāyana gotra. ― Altekar and Majumdar however state that the exact identification of Kudūra is not yet clear, with another village called Kodura near Ghantasala possibly the location of the ancient Kudūra. (Altekar, A.S. & Majumdar, R.C. The Vākāṭaka-Gupta Age, Motilal Banarsi Dass, 1954, p.63)

 -->

         </div>
